The '''Russia national under-19 football team''', controlled by the [[Russian Football Union]], represents [[Russia]] at the [[European Under-19 Football Championship]] and international [[friendly match]] fixtures at the under-19 age level.
==European Championships== === Introduction === Since the tournament adopted its current under-19 format in 2002, the Russia under-19s have failed to qualify for the [[UEFA European Under-19 Football Championship]]. They have, however, reached the second, or 'elite', qualification stage in all campaigns with the exception of 2002 when they were knocked out at the preliminary qualification stage.<ref>{{cite news| url= http://www.uefa.com/under19/history/index.html| title = UEFA under-19 European Championships history|accessdate=27 July 2011|publisher=[[Uefa.com]]}}</ref> They came closest to qualifying for the [[2011 UEFA European Under-19 Football Championship|2010 competition]], when they finished one point behind group winners Italy in the elite qualification stage.<ref>{{cite news| url= http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/ec-u19-2010.html| title = 2010 UEFA under-19 European Championships|accessdate=27 July 2011|publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation]]}}</ref>
In the [[2011 UEFA European Under-19 Football Championship qualification|2011 qualification campaign]], Russia again narrowly missed out on the finals, finishing second in group five of the elite qualifying stage, having drawn two games and won one against [[Israel national under-19 football team|Israel]].<ref>{{cite news| url= http://www.soccerway.com/matches/2011/05/21/europe/uefa-u19-championship/israel-under-19/russia-under-19/1054241/| title = Under-19 result: Israel 1-3 Russia|date=21 May 2011|accessdate=27 July 2011|publisher=soccerway.com}}</ref> The group winner was the [[Czech Republic national under-19 football team|Czech Republic]].<ref>{{cite news| url= http://www.uefa.com/under19/standings/round=2000082/group=2000651/index.html| title = 2011 UEFA under-19 European Championships elite stage: Group 5 final standings|accessdate=27 July 2011|publisher=[[Uefa.com]]}}</ref> The joint top scorers for Russia in the qualification campaign for 2011 were [[Aleksandr Kozlov (footballer)|Aleksandr Kozlov]] and [[Georgi Nurov]], who both scored two goals in three games.<ref>{{cite news| url= http://www.uefa.com/under19/statistics/round=2000081/players/type=topscorers/index.html| title = Top scorers: All qualifying stages, 2011 U-19 European Championships|accessdate=27 July 2011|publisher=[[Uefa.com]]}}</ref>
In the first qualification stage of the [[2012 UEFA European Under-19 Football Championship]], the Russia under-19s will face the under-19 representatives of [[Republic of Ireland national under-19 football team|Republic of Ireland]], [[Bosnia and Herzegovina national under-19 football team|Bosnia and Herzegovina]] and [[Bulgaria national under-19 football team|Bulgaria]]. All matches will be held in Bulgaria on 6-11 October 2011.<ref>{{cite news| url= http://www.uefa.com/under19/draws/season=2012/round=2000213/index.html| title = Qualifying group draw for 2012 U-19 European Championships|accessdate=27 July 2011|publisher=[[Uefa.com]]}}</ref>
